TANK CAR IN QUESTION IS A 2 COMPARTMENT VESSEL BUILT IN APRIL 1965.  COMPARTMENT A-2, CAPACITY 10,354 GALLONS WAS LOADED WITH ISOPROPANOL, UN1219, FLAMMABLE PRODUCT.  COMPARTMENT B-1, CAPACITY 10.384 GALLONS WAS LOADED WITH METHYLE ETHYL KETONE UN1193, FLAMMABLE, INITIAL INSPECTION OF LEAK INDICATED COMPARTMENT 2-A WAS LEAKING PRODUCT LEADED WITH ISOPROPANOL, UN1219, THE TANK HAD A CRACK THAT EXTENDED FROM THE BOTTOM OF SHELL UP 3'5" ON EACH SIDE AND SEPERATED APP. 1/16 - 1/18" ON THE BOTTOM OF SHELL.  CAR IN QUESTION WAS PLACED IN TRACK #45, AT 2138 HRS. AND DISCOVERED LEAKING AT APPROX. 2215 HRS., 2-6-95. CAR LOST COMPLETE LEAD OF 9,854 GALLONS FROM COMPARTMENT A-2 BEFORE ANY RESPONSE COULD BE COMPLETED BY RESPONSE TEAM.  EMERGENCY RESPONSE CO. USED A VACUUM TRUCK TO RECOVER ANY STANDING POOLS OF PRODUCT AND ISOLATED AREA UNTIL INSPECTION OF SITE FOR ENVIRONMENTAL PROBLEMS AND SITE CLEAN UP OPTIONS EVALUATED.  COMPARTMENT B-1, METHYL ETHYL KETONE, UN1193, WHICH WAS NOT LEAKING HAD ITS CONTENT TRANSFERRED INTO TANK TRUCK FOR MOVEMENT TO OTHER FACILITIES THIS OPERATIONS BEING COMPARMENT AT APPROX. 2200 HRS ON 2-7-95 BY EXXON RESPONSE TEAM.

DRIVER WAS LOADING DRUMS WHICH WERE VERY HEAVY (700-800 LBS). ONE OF THE DRUMS TIPPED OVER AND FLATTENED THE TOP LIP OF DRUM. DRIVER USED WRENCH AND HAMMER TO TIGHTEN BOLT ON THE 17-H DRUM. DRIVER THEN USED DRUM CART TO LEAN DRUM OVER ON SIDE TO SEE IF IT WOULD LEAK. THE DRUM DID NOT LEAK SO DRIVER LOADED THE DRUM. AT A LATER STOP THE CUSTOMER NOTICED THE DRUM WAS LEAKING. DRIVER PUT BOOMS AND ABSORBANT DOWN TO COLLECT SPILLED MATERIAL. HE OVERPACKED THE LEAKING DRUM AND PUT THE CLEAN UP MATERIAL IN OVERPACK AND DELIVERED TO STOP.

A VAN TRAILER CONTAINING HAZARDOUS WASTES WAS ENROUTE FROM ITT CORPORATION/EOPD DIVISION LOCATED AT 7635 PLANTATION ROAD IN ROANOKE, VA TO CLEAN HARBORS OF BRAINTREE, INC. LOCATED AT 385 QUINCY AVENUE IN BRAINTREE, MA. DURING A ROUTINE STOP AT CLEAN HARBORS OF CONNECTICUT, INC. LOCATED AT 51 BRODERICK ROAD IN BRISTOL CT, IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT APPROXIMATELY 8 GALLONS OF MATERIAL WAS RELEASED ONTO THE FLOOR OF THE VAN TRAILER ONTO A FULLY LINED CONCRETE CONTAINMENT AREA. FACILITY PERSONNEL IMMEDIATELY ABSORBED ALL FREE LIQUIDS WITH SPEEDY DRI AND OVERPACKED AND DAMAGED CONTAINER INTO A SUITABLE SALVAGE DRUM. IN ADDITION, A DRUM CONTAINING ADDITIONAL SPILL DEBRIS WAS GENERATED AND WAS SENT FOR DISPOSAL TO THE WASTE MANAGEMENT FACILITY IDENTIFIED ON THE ORINGINAL SHIPPING DOCUMENT. INSPECTION OF THE DAMAGED CONTAINER INDICATED THAT IT APPEARED THE CONTAINER WAS DAMAGED BY A FORK-LIFT CAUSING A SMALL SLIT TO DEVELOP IN THE UPPER PORTION OF THE CONTAINER. PRIOR TO DEPARTURE FROM THE SHIPPER'S LOCATION, ALL CONTAINERS WERE INSPECTED AND NO EVIDENCE OF DAMAGE WAS OBSERVED. LOADING PERSONNEL WILL BE RE-INSTRUCTED TO INSURE THAT DUE CARE AND ATTENTION IS TAKEN WHEN LOADING AND/OR MOVING DRUMS WITH A FORK-LIFT TO INSURE THAT CONTAINERS ARE NOT DAMAGED. IN ADDITION, ALL LOADING PERSONNEL WILL CONTINUE TO TAKE APPROPRIATE ACTIONS IN THE EVENT A CONTAINER IS FOUND NOT TO BE STRUCTURALLY SOUND (I.E. OVERPACKING INTO A SUITABLE SALVAGE DRUM, ETC.).

A VAN TRAILER CONTAINING HAZARDOUS WASTES WAS ENROUTE FROM BRAUN INTERTECH LOCATED AT 6875 WASHINGTON AVENUE IN MINNEAPOLIS, MN TO SPRING GROVE RESOURCES RECOVERY, INC. LOCATED AT 4879 SPRING GROVE AVENUE IN CINCINNATI, OH. DURING A ROUTINE STOP AT OSMONICS, INC. LOCATED AT 5951 CLEARWATER DRIVE IN MINNETONKA, MN IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT A PINHOLE LEAK HAD DEVELOPED ON THE SIDE OF THE DRUM RELEASING APPROXIMATELY 15 GALLONS OF MATERIAL ONTO THE FLOOR OF THE VAN TRAILER WHERE IT WAS PREVENTED FROM ESCAPING TO THE ENVIRONMENT. THE DRIVER IMMEDIATELY CONTACTED HIS HOME DISPATCHER WHO IN TURN DISPATCHED A EMERGENCY RESPONSE TEAM TO OVERPACK THE LEAKING DRUM AND CONDUCT THE CLEAN-UP OF THE TRAILER. IN ADDITION, THE MINNETONKA FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS CALLED TO APPRAISE THEM OF THE SITUATION. UPON ARRIVAL AT THE SCENE, THE MEMBERS OF THE EMERGENCY RESPONSE CREW ENTERED THE TRAILER AND ABSORBED ALL FREE LIQUIDS WITH A SUITABLE ABSORBENT MATERIAL. THE DAMAGED CONTAINER WAS THEN OVERPACKED INTO A SUITABLE SALVAGE DRUM FOR ADDITION, A DRUM CONTAINING SPILL DEBRIS WAS GENERATED AS A RESULT OF THE RELEASE AND WAS SENT TO THE WASTE MANAGEMENT FACILITY LISTED ON THE ORIGINAL DOCUMENT. PRIOR TO DEPARTURE FROM THE SHIPPER'S LOCATION, ALL CONTAINERS WERE INSPECTED AND NO EVIDENCE OF LEAKING OR DAMAGE WAS OBSERVED. ALL LOADING PERSONNEL WILL CONTINUE TO INSPECT EACH CONTAINER AS IT IS LOADED AND WILL TAKE APPROPRIATE ACTIONS IN THE EVENT A CONTAINER IS FOUND NOT TO BE STRUCTURALLY SOUND.

AT THAT POINT, I FLIPPED THE DRUM ON ITS SIDE AND KEPT THE HOLE AT THE HIGHEST POINT TO AVOID ANY MORE LEAKAGE, BRACING IT AGAINST THE WALL TO KEEP IT FROM FALLING AROUND WHEN BRINGING IT BACK TO THE TERMINAL. DURING A ROUTINE STOP AT SPRING GROVE RESOURCE RECOVERY, INC LOCATED AT 4879 SPRING GROVE AVENUE IN CINCINNATI, OH, IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT APPROXIMATELY 1 PINT OF LIQUID HAD ESCAPED FROM A SMALL CRACK THAT HAD DEVELOPED IN THE BOTTOM OF ONE OF THE CONTAINER.  THE MATERIAL WAS RELEASED ONTO THE FLOOR OF THE VAN TRAILER WHERE IT WAS PREVENTED FROM ESCAPING TO THE ENVIRONMENT.  FACILITY PERSONNEL IMMEDIATELY CONTAINED THE RELEASE, ABSORBED ALL FREE LIQUIDS WITH SPEEDI DRY AND OVERPACKED THE DAMAGED CONTAINER INTO A SUITABLE SALVAGE DRUM.  ALL CLEAN UP DEBRIS WAS PLACED IN THE SALVAGE DRUM AND WAS DISPOSED OF THROUGH THE WASTE MANAGEMENT FACILITY INDICATED ON THE SHIPPING DOCUMENT.  PRIOR TO DEPARTURE FROM THE SHIPPERS LOCATION, ALL CONTAINERS WERE INSPECTED AND NO EVIDENCE OF LEAKING OR DAMAGE WAS OBSERVED.  ALL DRIVERS AND LOADING PERSONNEL WILL CONTINUE TO INSPECT EACH CONTAINER AS IT IS LOADED AND TAKE APPROPRIATE ACTIONS IN THE EVENT A CONTAINER IS FOUND NOT TO BE STRUCTURALLY SOUND.

column168: SHIPMENT WAS LOADED AT THE ATL FACILITY ON THE REAR OF TRAILER 278712. THE SHIPMENT CONSISTED OF TWO 55 GALLON DRUMS THAT WERE PLACED ON A SKID AT THE REAR OF THE TRAILER. I CONTACTED CHEMTREC AND WAS ADVISED THAT IF WE OPENED THE TRAILER IN A WELL VENTILATED AREA WE COULD INVESTIGATE THE LEAKAGE.  THE TRAILER WAS OPENED AND WE DISCOVERED TWO 55 GALLON DRUMS LYING ON THEIR SIDES.  ONE DRUM WAS POSITIONED AT APPROX. A 15 DEGREE ANGLE ACROSS A SKID.  THE DRUM WAS LEAKING AT A POINT APPROX. 8 INCHES FROM THE TOP, WHERE THE DRUM HAD MADE CONTACT WITH THE SKID WHEN IT FELL OVER.  THE DRUM WAS REFUSED BY THE CONSIGNEE AND WILL BE RECOUPED IN A SALVAGE DRUM TO BE RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER.  REASON FOR SPILLAGE: DRUMS WERE LOADED ON THE TRAILER AND PLACED ON A SKID WITH NO VISIBLE MEANS OF SUPPORT.

column168: ON 2/9/95 AT 11:00 HOURS, THE TONGUE BROKE ON THE TRAILER OF A 1000 GAL. AMMONIA NURSE TANK. THIS OCCURED ON STATE ROUTE 84 AT MILEPOST 176. THE TANK ROLLED INTO A DITCH SHEARING OFF ALL THREE VALVES AND RELEASING ABOUT 400 GAL. OF AMMONIA IN A VAPOR. A SMALL VETERINARY LAB (4-6 EMPLOYEES) WAS IMMEDIATELY EVACUATED AND EMERGENCY PERSONNEL NOTIFIED. THE DRIVER ATTEMPTED TO SECURE THE SITE UNTIL EMERGENCY PERSONNEL ARRIVED. THE CASA GRANDE, AZ FIRE DEPT. AZ DEPT. OF PUBLIC SAFETY, AND THE AZ DEPT. OF ENVIR. QUALITY ARRIVED AND BEGAN CLEANUP OPERATIONS. ABOUT 400 PEOPLE WERE EVACUATED FROM A NEARBY SUBDIVISION AND A SECTION OF SR 84 WAS CLOSED. THE REMAINING AMMONIA WAS BLED OFF INTO WATER. THE INCIDENT WAS CLOSED AT 1920 HOURS. ROLL BARS WILL BE REINFORCED ON THE TANKS. TRAILERS ARE BEING REPLACED WITH STURDIER MODELS. DRIVERS HAVE BEEN GIVEN HM-126F AND HM-181 TRAINING.

AN ORDER WAS PLACED WITH TRI-GAS & OIL CO., INC. BY OWINGS AND SONS FROM MILLINGTON, MD. DOR 3,000 GALLONS OF DIESEL FUEL AND 4,000 GALLONS OF HEATING OIL. IT WAS DISPATCHED AS 4,000 GALLONS DIESEL FUEL AND 3,000 GALLONS OF HEATING OIL. TRI-GAS & OIL CO. WAS INFORMED BY OWINGS AND SONS THAT THE DIESEL FUEL TANK HAD A CAPACITY OF 6,000 GALLONS, BUT IN ACTUALLY IT IS 4,000 GALLONS. BEFORE MAKING THE DELIVERY THE TRI-GAS & OIL DELIVERY DRIVER GAUGED THE TANK AT 9" AND THINKING IT WAS A 6,000 GALLON TANK PROCEEDED TO UNLOAD THE FUEL. THE OVERFILL OCCURRED PRIOR TO THE COMPLETION OF THE DELIVERY. AN ESTIMATE OF 30 GALLONS RELEASED ONTO THE GROUND. SORBENT MATERIAL WAS APPLIED TO THE SPILL AREA. DUE TO THE RECENT RAIN, THE MAJORITY OF THE OIL SPILLED DID NOT SEEP INTO THE GROUND. THE SATURATED SORBENT MATERIAL WAS RAKED UP AND PLACED IN PLASTIC GARBAGE BAGS. ADDITIONAL SORBENT WAS PLACED OVER THE AFFECTED AREA. THE PROBLEM WAS TWO FOLD; CUSTOMER DID NOT KNOW SIZE OF TANK AND DISPATCHER HAD WRONG DELIVERY INSTRUCTIONS. TRI-GAS & OIL IS TRYING TO IMPROVE THIS COMMUNICATION GAP BY ASKING MORE QUESTION OF THE CUSTOMER. THERE SHOULD BE A LAW TO REQUIRE GALLON CAPACITY TO BE PUT ON EVERY CONTAINER NO MATTER WHERE LOCATED.
CUSTOMERS GAUGE BROKE CAUSING OVERFLOW.

WHILE UNLOADING A TRAILER A 300 GALLON TOTE WHICH WAS EMPTY, BUT DID CONTAIN SOME RESIDUE, IT WAS NOTICED THAT THERE WAS FROZEN SUBSTANCE ON THE FLOOR OF THE TRAILER WHICH APPEARED TO COME FROM THE CONTAINER. CHEMTREC WAS NOTIFIED AND THEY IN TURN CONTACTED THE CONSIGNEE.  HE ADVISED ME HOW TO HANDLE THE SITUATION SINCE THE SUBSTANCE WAS FROZEN.  IT APPEARS THAT THE VALVE WAS HEAVY TAPPED AND THE RESIDUE FROZE AND POSSIBLY CAME OUT THROUGH THE TAPE.  THIS IS ONLY SPECULATION ON MY PART, BUT I CANNOT COME UP WITH ANY OTHER EXPLANATION.

TRAILER 286647 FROM PENNSAUKEN NJ ARRIVED AT HARRISBURG PA TERMINAL AND ODOR WAS DETECTED TRAILER WAS ISOLATED AND CHEMTREC WAS ADVISED.  MSDS PAPER WORK WAS SECURED AND ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES WAS CALLED TO HANDLE. UPON INSPECTION BY ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES FOUND 1 GLASS JAR BROKEN OUT OF 2 JARS (ONLY ONE OF THE GLASS JARS HAD PROTECTIVE INNER WRAPPING AND WAS NOT BROKEN, OTHER JAR WITH NO PROTECTIVE WRAPPING WAS BROKEN) ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES NEUTRALIZED MATERIAL AND REPACKED MATERIAL AND CONTAMINATED CLEANUP MATERIAL IN OVERPACK DRUMS.  TRAILER WAS CLEANED BY ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES AND MADE SAFE FOR UNLOADING REST OF FREIGHT OFF TRAILER.

WHILE UNLOADING TRAILER, DARREN NOTICED THAT SOME OF THE BAGS WHERE TORN, APPARENTLY THEY WERE POKED BY A FORKLIFT WHEN THEY WERE LOADED.  DARREN CAME AND GOT ME.  I CLOSED OFF THE AREA AND CALLED HAZ-MAT RESPONSE INC. THEY INFORMED ME THAT I COULD CLEAN IT UP MYSELF, BUT TO WEAR SAFETY GOGGLES, GLOVES AND APRON.

WHILE INSPECTING CARGO ON TRI-STATES JOPLIN MO. TERMINAL, IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT ONE DRUM WAS LEAKING DUE TO A LOOSE BUNG.  LESS THAN ONE CUP OF MATERIAL LEAKED FROM AROUND BUNG AND WAS CONTAINED ON STEEL SECONDARY CONTAINMENT PAN.  BUNG WAS TIGHTENED AND LOAD PROCEEDED ON TO DESTINATION WITH NO FURTHER PROBLEM.  TRAILER FLOOR WAS CLEANED BY TSDF PERSONNEL.

WAS UNLOADING LAST COMPARTMENT OF DIESEL AND WALKED UP TO THE CAB OF THE TRACTOR.  I WAS COMPLETING SOME PAPER WORK WHEN MY TRAINEE SHOUTED SOMETHING & HIT THE BELLY VALVES.  AT THAT TIME I HAD SEEN THE TURN DOWN HAD JUMPED OFF & DIESEL WAS RUNNING OUT ON THE PARKING LOT.  WE TOOK CONTROL OF THE SPILL & CONTAINED IT WITH THE SPILL RAGS & CLEANED UP THE AREA.

VEHICLE "A" VEERED TO RIGHT TO AVOID COLLISION, LEAVING THE ROADWAY AND INTO DITCH, OVERTURNING. ROLLOVER PROTECTION BOX PLOWED UP GRASS AND DIRT AND THIS PUSHED AIR BLEED OFF VALVE ON TOP OF TRAILER TO OPEN SLIGHTLY, ALLOWING AN ESTIMATED 5 TO 7 GALLONS OF PRODUCT TO SPILL OUT ON TO GROUND. ALL PRODUCT WAS CLEANED UP BY CTL EMERGENCY RESPONSE PERSONNEL AND DISPOSED OF UNDER DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENTAL PROTECTION GUIDANCE AND PROCEDURES.

THE BARRELS ON THE END OF THE TRAILER WERE NOT ADEQUATELY SECURED AT LOADING.

THERE WAS NO LEAKAGE WHEN THE CAR WAS MOVED AND IT WAS RELEASED.

A "C" KIT WAS INSTALLED TO STOP THE LEAK.  JONES CHEMICALS EMERGENCY TEAM RESPONDED AND ASCERTAINED THAT THE VALVE LEAK COULD NOT BE REPAIRED ON SITE, BUT THAT THE CARGO TANK WOULD HAVE TO BE UNLOADED TO OUR PLANT FACILITY IN WARWICK, NY. LAST INSPECTED 2/5/95.  RETRAINING TO BE GIVEN AT JONES WARWICK LOCATION ON VALVE INSPECTIONS FOR CARGO TANKS.

DRIVER WAS IN ROUTE TO PATIENTS HOME WHEN TRANSMISSION FAILED PULLING A GRADE.  DRIVER WAS ABLE TO ALLOW TRUCK TO ROLL BACK DOWN HILL AND OFF TO SIDE OF ROAD IN GRAVEL AREA.  HE PROCEEDED TO NEAREST HOME TO USE PHONE CALL FOR ASSISTANCE BUT NO ONE WAS THERE SO HE WENT TO A SECOND HOME AND WAS ABLE TO CALL OFFICE.  UPON LEAVING HOUSE HE NOTICED SMOKE COMING FROM UNDER HOOD AND TURNED TO ASK RESIDENT TO CALL FIRE DEPARTMENT FOR HELP. WHEN TRYING TO REACH FIRE EXTINGUISHER HE WAS NOT ABLE TO BECAUSE THE CAB WAS FILLED WITH SMOKE.  WHEN THE FIRE AND RESCUE ARRIVED THE WAS TOTALLY ENGULFED IN FLAMES AND THE ONLY THING THE FIREMAN COULD WAS TRY TO KEEP THE FLAMES UNDER CONTROL AND THE LOX TANKS COOL, WHICH THEY DID AND ALLOW THE BURSTING DISC TO FUNCTION PROPERLY, TO RELIEVE PRESSURE SLOWLY.  NO ONE WAS INJURED BUT ONE LADY, WHOSE PHONE WE USED, WAS EVACUATED UNTIL IT WAS SAFE TO RETURN.

column168: A VAN TRAILER CONTAINING HAZARDOUS WASTE WAS ENROUTE FROM SPRING GROVE RESOURCE RECOVERY, INC.  LOCATED AT 4879 SPRING GROVE AVENUE IN CINCINNATI, OH TO ECOVA LOCATED ON HIGHWAY 71, 5 MILES SOUTH OF KIMBALL NEBRASKE.  UPON ARRIVAL AT THE DESTINATION FACILITY, IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT APPROXIMATELY 6 OUNCES OF MATERIAL HAD ESCAPED FROM THE TOP LID OF ONE OF THE CONTAINERS ONTO THE FLOOR OF THE VAN TRAILER WHERE IT WAS PREVENTED FROM ESCAPING TO THE ENVIRONMENT.  INSPECTION OF THE CONTAINER. FACILITY PERSONNEL IMMEDIATELY CONTAINED THE RELEASE, ABSORBED ALL FREE LIQUIDS WITH SPEEDI DRY AND RE0TIGHTENED THE CLOSURE DEVICE.  ALL CLEAN UP DEBRIS WAS CONTAINERIZED AND DISPOSED OF THROUGH THE WASTE MANAGEMENT FACILITY INDICATED ON THE SHIPPING DOCUMENT.  PRIOR TO DEPARTURE FROM THE SHIPPER'S LOCATION, ALL CONTAINERS WERE INSPECTED AND NO EVIDENCE OF LEAKING OR DAMAGE WAS OBSERVED.  ALL DRIVERS AND LOADING PERSONNEL WILL CONTINUE TO INSPECT EACH CONTAINER AS IT IS LOADED AND TAKE APPROPRIATE ACTIONS IN THE EVENT A CONTAINER IS FOUND NOT TO BE STRUCTURALLY SOUND. IN ADDITION, ALL DRIVERS AND LOADING PERSONNEL WILL BE RE-INSTRUCTED TO INSPECT THE CLOSURE OF ALL CONTAINERS TO INSURE THAT ALL CONTAINERS ARE SECURELY CLOSED.

column168: A MINOR SPILL ESTIMATED LESS THAN 8 1/2 GALLONS DISCOVERED AT DOCKING OPERATION (SEE ATTACHED). -INCIDENT SUMMARY ATTACHED -BILL OF LADING -MSDS -ASHLAND LABEL.  ON MONDAY 2/27/95, A MINOR LEAK WAS DISCOVERED  WHILE UNLOADING A VAN/TRAILER AT THE LOCATION NOTED AS FOLLOWS:  ASHLAND CHEMICAL 3322 NW 3RD STREET PORTLAND, OR 97210.  ASHLAND CHEMICAL UTILIZED THEIR PERSONNEL FOR QUALIFIED ASSESSMENT AND CORRECTIVE ACTION.  THE LOCATION OF THE LEAK IS DESCRIBED ON A SINGLE DRUM AT THE BASE "CHIME" APPEARING THE SIZE OF A "PIN HOLE".  THE SPILL IS QUANTIFIED LESS THAN 8-1/2 GALLONS.  NO NEGATIVE ENVIRONMENTAL IMPACT ON PHYSICAL DAMAGE TO THE VAN/TRAILER IS NOTED.  THE DRUM WAS SEGREGATED AND OVERPACKED.  NO WASTE WAS GENERATED AS A RESULT OF CLEANUP.  PRODUCT WAS RECOVERED WITHIN THE OVERPACK.  VENTILATION CAUSED VAPORIZATION OF MOST OF THE SPILLAGE. PRODUCT IS RECOVERED FOR REGENERATION AND "BENEFICIAL USE".  IT IS SPECULATED THAT THE BASE OF THE DRUM CAME IN CONTACT WITH A PROTRUDING "BOLT HEAD" WITHIN THE TRAILER THEREBY CAUSING A "PIN HOLE" LEAK IN THE BASE OF THE DRUM.  LOAD/UNLOAD PROCEDURES ARE REVIEWED WITH PERSONNEL TO MINIMIZE ANY SIMILAR AND FUTURE OCCURRENCE.  WE ENCLOSE A COPY OF MSDS, BILL OF LADING, DRUM LABEL AND PHOTOGRAPHS FOR YOUR REVIEW AND RECORD.

column168: ON FEBRUARY 2, 1995, SORT LEAD, STEVE CHERRYHOLMES, CONTACTED HAZ-MAT DISPATCH VIA RADIO AND REPORTED THAT HE HAD A PACKAGE THAT WAS LEAKING A DARK BROWN LIQUID AND THAT IT SMELLED LIKE SOME TYPE OF PRIMER. PART-TIME SPILL TECHNICIAN SHARON LOVE ACKNOWLEDGE THE CALL AND RESPONDED TO HIS LOCATION IN BUILDING "C", UPSTAIRS, IN SECONDARY 8. UPON ARRIVAL, PART-TIME SPILL TECHNICIAN SHARON LOVE FOUND THE PACKAGE IN QUESTION AND OPENED THE PACKAGE, FINDING TWO INNER FIBERBOARD BOXES, EACH BEARING A FLAMMABLE LIQUID, CLASS 3 LABEL. AT THIS TIME, SHE DOUBLE-BAGGED THE PACKAGE AND RETURNED TO THE HAZARDOUS MATERIAL SORT BUILDING 207 AND ADVISED HAZARDOUS MATERIAL COORDINATOR BEN TAYLOR OF WHAT SHE HAD. HAZARDOUS MATERIALS COORDINATOR BEN TAYLOR OPENED THE PLASTIC BAGS AND THEN OPENED THE OUTER MOST FIBERBOARD BOX AND ALSO NOTICED TWO INNER FIBERBOARD BOXES THAT WERE LABELED "FLAMMABLE LIQUID".  BEN TAYLOR THEN TOOK BOTH INNER BOXES OUT AND FOUND THAT THEY WERE ALSO MARKED ON THE ADJACENT SIDES WITH THE FOLLOWING INFORMATION: COATING SOLUTION, UN1139, FLAMMABLE. THE MANUFACTURERS WARNING LABEL ON EACH BOX STATED THAT THE PRIMER CONTAINED NAPTHA, HEPTANES AND MINERAL SPIRITS. FURTHER INSPECTION OF THE INNER CONTENTS OF EACH BOX REVEALED 12 X 16 OX. (473 ML) PLASTIC RECEPTACLES LEAK AN ESTIMATED QUANTITY OF 3 OZS. (90 ML) AND THE OTHER BOX, 4 OF THE 12 INNER PLASTIC RECEPTACLES LEAKED APPROXIMATELY 1 OZ. (30ML). THERE ARE TWO FACTORS THAT ARE BELIEVED TO HAVE CONTRIBUTED TO THIS SHIPMENT LEAKING: 1. THE METAL CAPS ON THE PLASTIC RECEPTACLES WERE LOOSE.  2. THE TWO INNER BOXES EACH CONTAINING THE 12 X 16 OZ. PLASTIC RECEPTACLES WERE PLACED IN THE LARGER OUTER MOST FIBERBOARD BOX OR OVERPACK SIDEWAYS AGAINST THE ORIENTATION OF THE TOP CLOSURES. THE SHIPMENT WAS THEN PLACED BACK INTO 3 PLASTIC BAGS AND PLACED IN OUR SECURITY CAGE UNDER LOCK AND KEY UNTIL THE FEDERAL AVIATION ADMINISTRATION COULD SEND AGENTS TO OUR FACILITY TO INVESTIGATE THE SHIPMENT IN QUESTION.

column62: Dropped; Improper Preparation for Transportation; Dropped; Improper Preparation for Transportation
column168: ON FEBUARY 7, 1995, MARY LATHREM, HAZARDOUS MATERIAL LEAD, REPORTED A LEAK FROM A CARGO "C" FREIGHT CONTAINER IN THE HAZARDOUS MATERIAL SORT FACILITY. THE HAZARDOUS MATERIAL SORT FACILITY IS LOCATED AT ABX AIR, INC., 145 HUNTER DRIVE, WILMINGTON, OHIO 45177. HAZARDOUS MATERIAL COORDINATOR ADDIE CAMPTON AND PART-TIME SPILL TECHNICIAN DIANE FIGUEROA RESPONDED TO A SPILL. UPON ARRIVAL TO THE SPILL, WE TOOK ADDITIONAL PRECAUTIONS AND DONNED OUR PERSONAL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT. WE FIRST OBSERVED A SILVERY LIQUID IN THE BOTTOM OF A CARGO FREIGHT "C" CONTAINER. WE DISCOVERED A SHIPMENT LEAKING. UPON INVESTIGATION OF THE INNER CONTENTS, WE FOUND APPROXIMATELY 6 TO 8 PLASTIC RECEPTACLES WITH SCREW TYPE CLOSURES. 3 OF THE RECEPTACLES HAD CRACKED BOTTOMS. THE CONTENTS OF THE 3 RECEPTACLES WERE LOST. WHILE ON SCENE, WORKING TO CONTAIN THE SPILL, THE SPILL TEAM DISCOVERED 2 MORE SHIPMENTS THAT WERE LEAKING. THE SHIPMENTS THAT WERE LEAKING WERE A 3 OF 7 PIECE SHIPMENT. ALL OF THE SHIPMENT THAT WERE LEAKING CONTAINED PLASTIC RECEPTACLES THAT HAD APPROXIMATELY 12 OUNCES OF PRODUCT EACH. THE INNER FIBERBOARD BOX DID NOT CONTAIN ENOUGH CUSHIONING MATERIAL TO PREVENT BREAKAGE OF THE INNER RECEPTACLES. AFTER DOCUMENTING THE REASON FOR THE SHIPMENTS LEAKING, THE SHIPMENT WERE THEN PLACED IN 2 PLASTIC BAGS WITH ABSORBENT MATERIAL AND PUT IN A RECOVERY DRUM. THIS 7 LOT SHIPMENT WAS PLACED IN A RECOVERY DRUM BECAUSE OF THE APPARENT FAILURE OF THE PACKAGING. THE OUTER FIBERBOARD BOXES WERE CLEARLY MARKED AND LABELED AS A HAZARDOUS MATERIAL. PROPER CERTIFICATION DID ACCOMPANY THIS SHIPMENT. IN ADDITION, THE PACKAGE SPECIFICATION IDENTIFICATION MANUFACTURERS SEAL WAS OBSCURED BY A LOT LABEL. THE SHIPMENT WAS THEN PREPARED TO RETURN TO THE SHIPPER. THE ONLY THEORY WE HAVE FOR THE SHIPMENT PACKAGING FAILURE WAS THAT THE PACKAGE DID NOT CONTAIN ENOUGH INNER CUSHIONING MATERIAL TO PROTECT THE INNER CONTENTS OF THE SHIPMENT. THE D.O.T. REFERENCE USE IS CFR 172.312 (C) (3). WE WERE CLEAR OF THE SCENE AT 02:30.

WHILE MAKING HAZARDOUS MATERIALS SHIPMENT INSPECTIONS AT THE UPRR LIVONIA YARD, FRA H/M INSPECTOR JIM DUNCAN OBSERVED LIQUID DRIPPING FROM THE BOTTOM OUTLET NOZZLE CAP OF CAR UTLX 200109.  DUNCAN NOTIFIED UPRR MMM DAVE MEYERS.  MEYERS HAD THE CAR ISOLATED AT LIVONIA AND PLACED IN A BUCKET BENEATH THE CAR TO CONTAIN ANY SPILLAGE.  THE DRIPPING WAS AT A RATE OF ABOUT ONE DROP PER MINUTE.  MEYERS NOTIFIED UPRR REG. MGR. CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, T.M. ROBINSON.  MEYERS ALSO NOTIFIED CHEMTREC AND THE SHIPPER.  ROBINSON RESPONDED TO LIVONIA FROM MONROE, LOUISIANA AND ARRIVED ON SCENE AT ABOUT 1900 HOURS.  MEYERS AND ROBINSON INSPECTED THE CAR AND FOUND THAT THE DRIPPAGE HAD STOPPED.  ROBINSON REMOVED FRAYED ON ONE SIDE.  THE GASKET WAS TURNED OVER AND REINSTALLED. ROBINSON RESECURED THE NOZZLE CAP WITH AN APPROPRIATE WRENCH.  IT SHOULD BE NOTED THAT DURING THE APPROXIMATELY 10 MINUTES THAT THE NOZZLE CAP WAS OFF, NO LEAKAGE WAS OBSERVED FROM THE BOTTOM OPERATED BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE. THE CAR WAS RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT ONTO DESTINATION.  ROBINSON MADE FOLLOW UP CONTACT WITH MR. CHRIS FRILOUX OF CYTECH AND MR. JERRY WATKINS OF WHITAKER OIL.  BOTH GENTLEMAN STATED THAT THEY WOULD FOLLOW UP WITH THEIR PERSONNEL AND MAKE SURE THAT THE GASKET IN QUESTION IN REPLACED BEFORE THE CAR IS RELOADED.

ALUMINUM TANKS WERE DROPPED AT THE ALBEMARBLE CORPORATION-PASADENA ON FEBRUARY 22, 1995 TO BE LOADED AT A FUTURE DATE. AT THE ALBEMARBLE CORPORTATION THEN TRANSPORTED TO THE CHEMICAL WASTE MANAGEMENT FACILITY IN ORANGE, TEXAS. THE MATERIAL REACTED WITH THE ALUMINUN TANK CAUSING A RELEASE OF MATERIAL FROM TRAILER A; TRAILER B WAS OFFLOADED BEFORE ITS CONTENTS WERE RELEASED. THE LIQUID RELEASED FROM TRAILER A WAS CONTAINED WITHIN THE DRAINAGE DITCH ADJACENT TO THE HOLDING FACILITY. THE NECESSARY ENVIRONMENTAL REMEDIATION ITS UNDER THE DIRECTION OF THE TEXAS NATURAL RESOURCE CONSERVATION COMMISSION. THE SPILL WAS REPORTED TO THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER (REPORT #281423). IN CONCLUSION, A SHIPPER MUST SPECIFY THE PROPER TYPE OF CONTAINER FOR THE MATERIAL THE SHIPPER WANTS TO HAVE TRANSPORTED BY THE CARRIER.

column168: ON 022095 APPROXIMATELY 9PM, REEDER RECEIVED A CALL FROM MTO MCCARTHY THAT A SWITCHMAN HAS SMELLED SOMETHING COMING FROM THE ABOVE CAR. REEDER RECOMMENDED THAT THE CAR BE ISOLATED FOR A DISTANCES OF 500' (10 CAR LENGTHS) IN ALL DIRECTIONS. NORMAL ACTIVITIES COULD CONTINUE OUTSIDE THAT AREA. CHEMTREC WAS NOTIFIED AND ASKED FOR SHIPPER CONTACT. WHEN THE SHIPPER CALLED, REEDER ADVISED THEM OF THE SITUATION AND ASKED FOR RESPONSE ASSISTANCE. WHEN THE TEAM LEADER ADVISED IT WOULD TAKE HIM APPROXIMATELY 45 MINUTES TO ARRIVE AND THE TEAM 1.5 TO 2 HOURS, REEDER STATED THE HOUSTON FIRE DEPARTMENT HAZARDOUS MATERIAL TEAM WOULD BE CALLED TO ASSIST. REEDER MET THE RESPONDERS AND PROVIDED THE SHIPPING PAPERS. MTO JOHN RICE ASSISTED IN ARRANGING FOR A SWITCH ENGINE AND ABOUT 25 CARS TO REACH INTO THE YARD AND PULL THE LEAKING CAR OUT. REEDER AND TWO FIREMEN RODE THE CUT INTO THE YARD TO COUPLE AND UNCOUPLE CARS AS NECESSARY. THE LEAKING CAR WAS PULLED TO A SAFE LOCATION UNDER A LIGHT POLE. THERE THE LEAK WAS DISCOVERED AT THE BLIND FLANGE ON THE VAPOR VALVE. THE LEAK WAS CONFIRMED USING "SNOOP" AND A SONIC LEAK DETECTOR PROVIDED BY THE HAZ MAT TEAM. THE BOLTS ON THE FLANGE WERE NOT WRENCH TIGHT. WHEN THE BOLTS WERE TIGHTENED, THE LEAK STOPPED. AGAIN THIS WAS CONFIRMED WITH "SNOOP" AND THE LEAK DETECTOR. THE AREA WAS DECLARED SAFE AND NORMAL ACTIVITIES RESUMED AROUND 1230AM. THE CAR WAS WASHED BY THE SHIPPER'S TEAM TO REMOVED ANY REMAINING ODOR. IT WAS THEN RETURNED TO THEIR FACILITY FOR INSPECTION.

IT WAS NOTED THAT THE LOCKING BAR ASSEMBLY NEEDS TO BE REPLACED.  CHEMTREC AND THE SHIPPER NOTIFIED.  SHIPPER COMINCO LIMITED VANCOUVER, MR. RICHARD WEGENER RISK CONTROL, STATE THEY WOULD HAVE THE CAR RETURNED TO CANADA FOR REPAIR.

column168: DEAN C. COOPER, MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS NOTIFIED BY DOUG MAUGHN, MANAGER, YARD OPERATIONS, YERMO, CALIFORNIA, WAS ADVISED THE WEST END SWITCH JOB NOTED A TANK CAR LEAKING FROM THE TOP PORTION OF THE CAR DURING NORMAL SWITCHING OPERATIONS. THE CAR WAS SET TO YARD TRACK #208 AND ISOLATED PENDING INSPECTION. MANAGER COOPER DROVE TO THE YERMO YARD FACILITY, INSPECTED THE TANK CAR, AND DEVELOPED THE SOURCE OF THE LEAK TO BE FROM A LOOSE CLOSURE CAP ON THE 2" LIQUID LINE. THE CAP COULD BE TURNED BY HAND AND WOULD INDICATE THE CAR WAS NOT PROPERLY SECURED FOR SHIPMENT, WHICH WOULD ACCOUNT FOR THE PRODUCT BEING RELEASED EACH TIME THE CAR WAS MOVED. THE CAP WAS PROPERLY SECURED UTILIZING AN APPROPRIATE PIPE WRENCH. THE REMAINING VALVES AND FITTINGS WERE ALSO INSPECTED AND FOUND TO BE SECURE. THE CAR WAS THEN RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT ONTO THE CONSIGNEE. DUE TO THE MINIMAL AMOUNT AND TYPE OF PRODUCT RELEASED, NOTIFICATIONS WERE ONLY MADE TO CHEMTREC FOR REPORTING PURPOSES, AND TO THE SHIPPER FOR CORRECTIVE ACTION.

column168: BUREAU OF EXPLOSIVES HAZ MAT INSPECTOR, BILL OERTLY WAS INSPECTING TANK CARS IN CSXT'S HAMLET, NC. YARD WHEN HE FOUND A TANK CAR THAT WAS LEAKING FROM THE BOTTOM OUTLET. HE INSPECTED THE CAR AND FOUND THAT IT WAS ALSO LEAKING FROM AROUND THE MANWAY COVER. THE SECUREMENT BOLTS ON THE MANWAY COVER WERE NOT WRENCH TIGHT. OERTLY TIGHTENED THE BOLTS WITH A WRENCH. HE ALSO FOUND THAT BOTTOM OUTLET EXTENSION CAP WAS ONLY HAND TIGHT. HE TIGHTENED THE CAP WITH A WRENCH AND THE LEAK STOPPED. THE SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED VIA CHEMTREC. THE CAR WAS RELEASED.

GREGORY BROTHERS'S TRUCKING WAS TRANSFERRING SULFURIC ACID FROM A TANK CAR TO A TRUCK AT THE BULK DISTRIBUTION SERVICE (BIDS) FACILITY IN CHILLICOTHE, OH. A 3/4 INCH AIR HOSE WAS ATTACHED TO THE TRANSFER HOSE WITH A VALVE. THIS VALVE WAS OPEN ALLOWING ACID TO BACK INTO THE AIR HOSE. THE AIR HOSE CRACKED AND SPRAYED ACID INTO THE DRIVER/OPERATOR. THE DRIVER, LYN JACKSON, CLOSED ALL TRANSFER VALVES AND DROVE TO CSXT'S YARD OFFICE. HE WAS WASHED OFF AND TAKEN TO THE HOSPITAL BY AMBULANCE. MR. JACKSON WAS WEARING GOGGLES AND A SPLASH SUIT HE RECEIVED SLIGHT BURNS TO HIS CHEEK AND LIP; GIVEN SOME SALVE AND RELEASED FROM THE HOSPITAL. LOCAL FIRE AND POLICE RESPONDED. GREGORY BROTHERS SENT ANOTHER OPERATOR WHO FINISHED THE TRANSFER OPERATION AND NEUTRALIZED THE SPILLED ACID WITH LIME.

MANAGER COOPER DROVE TO THE YERMO YARD FACILITY, INSPECTED THE CAR AND DEVELOPED THE SOURCE OF THE LEAK TO BE FROM A BURST FRANGIBLE DISC IN THE SAFETY VENT ASSEMBLY ATTACHED TO THE MANWAY COVER PLATE. THE SAFETY VENT, A STANDARD MIDLAND BAFFLE, WAS DISASSEMBLED, AND THE RUPTURE DISC REPLACED WITH A LIKE TYPE BS&B 100 POUND STAINLESS/TEFLON TYPE DISC. THE SAFETY VENT WAS REASSEMBLED AND THE REMAINING VALVES AND FITTINGS WERE ALSO INSPECTED AND FOUND TO BE INTACT. THE CAR WAS THEN RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT ONTO THE CONSIGNEE. NOTIFICATIONS WERE ONLY MADE TO CHEMTREC AND THE SHIPPER FOR NOTIFICATION PURPOSES ONLY.

MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, D.A.LOW, WAS NOTIFIED BY CHEYENNE YARD MASTER, THAT TANK CAR TGOX 30675, MTBE, WAS NOTED LEAKING FROM TOP AREA AND TANK CAR WOULD BE ISOLATED ON SOUTH RIP TRACKS. INSPECTION REVEALED THAT LEAK WAS COMING FROM BASE OF THE TWO-INCH UNLOADING CONNECTION VALVE. MANAGER, D.A.LOW, NOTED THAT BASE OF VALVE WAS REPAIRED BY HIM AT 1500 HOURS, 9/28/94, DOT REPORT FILED. DUE TO THE CONDITION OF THE VALVE GASKET (GORTEX) AND BASE OF VALVE, CAR WAS BAD ORDERED AND SENT BACK TO COASTAL CHEM FOR OFF-LOADING. TIROME SVEHLA, COASTAL CHEM WAS NOTIFIED OF EXCEPTIONS. DEAN C. COOPER, MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS NOTIFIED BY JOE MOSHIER, SUPERVISOR, YARD OPERATIONS, YEROM, CALIFORNIA, STATING THAT A TANK CAR WAS NOTED LEAKING FROM THE BOTTOM OUTLET DURING NORMAL SWITCHING OPERATIONS AT THE WEST END OF THE YERMO YARD. THE TANK CAR WAS SET TO THE CABOOSE TRACK AND ISOLATED PENDING INSPECTION. MANAGER COOPER DROVE TO THE YERMO YARD FACILITY, INSPECTED THE CAR, AND DEVELOPED THE SOURCE OF THE LEAK TO BE FROM WITHIN THE BOTTOM SKID PLATE CLOSURE THAT PROTECTS THE BOTTOM OUTLET.  THERE WAS NO VISIBLE LEAKS AROUND THE FLANGE FOR THE BOTTOM OUTLET. THE CAR ONLY LEAKED WHEN BEING MOVED, AND ONLY FROM THE END OPENINGS OF THE SKID PLATE. THERE IS AN OPENING ON BOTH ENDS OF THE SKID WHERE THE PLATE CONTOURS TO AND AGAINST THE ROUNDED UNDER BELLY OF THE TANK CAR, WHICH IS THE ONLY AREA OF THE PROTECTIVE PLATE THAT IS NOT WELDED. THE MATERIAL DRIPPING FROM THIS AREA WAS PH TESTED AND FOUND TO BE IN THE 0 TO 1 PH RANGE, INDICATION IT WAS NOT WATER ACCUMULATION. THERE WERE ALSO VERY HEAVY RUST RUNS FROM BOTH OPEN ENDS OF THE PROTECTIVE PLATE, WHICH WOULD INDICATE THIS CAR HAD BEEN LEAKING FOR SOME TIME. AS THIS CAR CONTAINED A RESIDUE PRODUCT, ARRANGEMENTS WERE MADE THROUGH DON LARUE, V.P., OPERATIONS, NU WEST INDUSTRIES, TO HAVE THE RESIDUE PUMPED OFF AND DELIVERED TO LOS ANGELES CHEMICAL. APPROXIMATELY 50 GALLONS OF RESIDUE WAS REMOVED FROM THE CAR THROUGH THE BOTTOM OUTLET UTILIZING A VACUUM TRUCK. DUE TO THE AMOUNT OF SLUDGE IN THE BOTTOM OF THE TANK CAR, A VISUAL FIX ON THE SOURCE OF THE LEAK WAS NOT POSSIBLE FROM THE MANWAY. THE OPEN EDGES OF THE PLATE WERE PUTTIED TO PREVENT ANY ADDITIONAL LEAKAGE. THE CAR WAS MOVED SEVERAL TIMES TO VERIFY SECUREMENT, THEN RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT ONTO THE CONSIGNEE. NOTIFICATIONS WERE ONLY MADE TO CHEMTREC FOR NOTIFICATION PURPOSES, AND TO THE CAR OWNER FOR CORRECTIVE ACTION.

ON 2-22-95 SORTER, CONNIER SPURLOCK REPORTED A SHIPMENT LEAKING AND EMITTING AN ODOR, IN THE MAIN SORT.  UPON ARRIVAL ON THE SCENE I, MICHAEL A. FRYE, HAZARDOUS MATERIALS COORDINATOR AND HAZARDOUS MATERIALS TECHNICIAN, DAVID JARRELL INVESTIGATED THE FIBERBOARD BOX.  INSIDE THE FIBERBOARD BOX WERE THREE AEROSOL RECEPTACLES AND ONE PLASTIC RECEPTACLE. THE PLASTIC RECEPTACLE HAS A SCREW TYPE CLOSURE WITH NO POSITIVE MEANS TO SECURE.  THERE WAS A SMALL CRACK IN THE BOTTOM OF THE PLASTIC RECEPTACLE WHICH ALLOWED SOME OF THE LIQUID CONTENTS TO LEAK.  MARKED ON THE LABEL OF THE PLASTIC RECEPTACLE WAS "LYSOL I.C., TOILET.  BOWL DISENFECTANT CLEANER".  ALSO INSIDE THE FIBERBOARD BOX WERE MATERIAL SAFETY DATA SHEETS FOR EACH PRODUCT.  THERE WERE NO MARKINGS, LABELS OR PROPER CERTIFICATION ACCOMPANYING THIS SHIPMENT TO INDICATE THAT ITS CONTENTS WERE REGULATED AS HAZARDOUS MATERIALS.  THIS SHIPMENT IS AT THE HAZMAT SORT, UNDER LOCK AND KEY, IN THE SECURTIY CAGE.

A LARGE SKID OF STEEL WAS LOADED NEXT TO ONE SKID CONTAINING 30 5-GALLON PAILS POISONOUS LIQUID, CORROSIVE, N.O.S. (DICYCLOHEXYLMETHANE).  ONE PAIL WAS PUNCTURED BECAUSE NO DUNNAGE WAS USED TO PROTECT THE HAZARDOUS MATERIAL.  PER JEFF ZARZECKI AT DENNIS CHEMICAL, THE SPILL WAS ABSORBED WITH OIL DRY, AS WELL AS THE REMAINING PRODUCT IN THE PAIL.  ONCE EXPOSED TO AIR AND COMBINED W/OIL DRY, THIS PRODUCT HARDENS AND IS NO LONGER HAZARDOUS.  THE HARDENED RESIDUE CAN BE DUMPED, WHICH WAS DONE LOCALLY. IN THE FUTURE, PROPER LOADING TECHNIQUES WILL BE UTILIZED TO AVOID THIS SITUATION.

column168: AT APPROX. 1855 ON FEB. 22, 1995, DRIVER CRAIG MACKENZIE OBSERVED A "PUFF OF SMOKE" COMING OUT OF THE OLIN HUNT SHIPMENT ON THE DOCK.  HE TOLD THE DISPATCHER, DON STEINBORN, AND ALERTED ANOTHER DRIVER TOM GRAY WHO WAS ON THE DOCK.  DON CALLED 911 AND TAMMY, THE OFFICE GIRL, CALLED CHEMTREC. TOM GRAY TOOK IT UPON HIMSELF TO LOAD THIS PRODUCT ON A TRAILER AT THE DOCK AND YELLED TO A DRIVER IN THE YARD TO PULL THIS TRAILER OUT INTO THE YARD. LARRY GILROY PULLED THE TRAILER OUT IN THE YARD WITH THE DOOR OPEN. THE ROCKFORD, IL HAZMAT TEAM AND NUMBEROUS FIRE FIGHTERS AND TRUCKS WERE ON THE SCENE WITHIN 10-15 MINUTES.  THEY TOOK CONTROL OF THE SITUATION IMMEDIATELY.  THIS WAS AN INTERMITTENT LEAK THAT THEY STOPPED BY PUTTING THE CYLINDER UNDER DRY ICE.  A HAZMAT TEAM FOR KERR-MCGEE FLEW IN THE ROCKFORD AND WERE ON THE SCENE TO RESEAL THE CYLINDER THE MORNING OF 2/23/95.  THE ROCKFORD FIRE DEPT. WAS ALSO ON THE SCENE AS A BACK UP PRECAUTION.
